y in Canada. Contributors include economists, sociologists, philosophers, and political scientists, and the discussion ranges from frameworks for thinking about inequality, to original analyses using Canadian data, to assessments of significant policy issues, methodologies, and research directions. What emerges is the most detailed picture of inequality in Canada to date and, disturbingly, one that shows signs of us becoming a less just society. An invaluable source of information for policy makers, researchers, and students from a broad variety of disciplines, Dimensions of Inequality in Canada will also appeal to readers interested or involved in public debates over inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aBanting, Keith G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeach, Charles M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoudarbat, Brahim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheung, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossley, Thomas F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenberg, Avigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortin, Nicole M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrenette, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGee, Ellen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabb, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, David A., eeditor.4edt4http://id